":"1448","1425":"1425","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","about 1449":"about 1449","1420":"1420","1474":"1474","about 1500":"about 1500","1518":"1518","about 1471":"about 1471","1438":"1438","1504":"1504","Of Benenden,Kent,Eng":"Benenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Louth, County Louth, Ireland":"Louth, County Louth, Ireland","England":"England","Benenden, Kent, England":"Benenden, Kent, England","London, London, England, United Kingdom":"London, England, United Kingdom","Benenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Benenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Moore","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>more</i> ‘moor, marsh, fen’ (Old English <i>mōr</i>), hence a topographic name for someone who lived in such a place, or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, as for example Moore in Cheshire or More in Shropshire.","English (of Norman origin): ethnic name from Old French <i>more</i> ‘Moor’, either someone from North Africa or, more often, a nickname for someone thought to resemble a Moor. Compare   Morrell   and   Moreau  .","English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal name <i>More</i> (Old French <i>More</i>, <i>Maur</i>, Latin <i>Maurus</i>), originally denoting either ‘Moor’ or someone with a swarthy complexion (compare   Morrell  ,   Morrin  ,   Morris  , and sense 2 above). There was a 6th-century Christian saint of this name."],"variants":[{"name":"Moor","meanings":["English, Irish, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Moore  .","German: variant of   Mohr  .","Dutch (also <b>De Moor</b>): nickname for a man of swarthy complexion, from Middle Dutch <i>moor</i> ‘Moor’ (from Latin <i>maurus</i>), or a topographic or habitational name referring to a house distinguished by the sign of a Moor. Compare   De Moor  ."]},{"name":"More","meanings":["French: nickname for a dark-skinned man, from a diminutive of Old French <i>more</i> ‘Moor’ (see   More  )."]},{"name":"Morrin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot.","English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Morin</i>, a diminutive of <i>More</i> (Old French <i>More</i>, <i>Maur</i>, Latin <i>Maurus</i>); see   Moore   2 and 3.","English: perhaps sometimes from the Middle English personal name <i>Morwin</i> (Old English <i>Mōrwine</i>, the first element of which is uncertain and the second <i>wine</i> ‘friend’)."]},{"name":"Mauro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Sal, Domenic, Giuseppe, Antonio, Carmine, Carmelo, Domenico, Gaetano, Nino, Pasquale.","Italian (mainly southern): from the personal name <i>Mauro</i>, derived from the Latin personal and ethnic name <i>Maurus</i>, borne by various early Christian saints and meaning ‘Moor, North African’. Compare   Moore   and   Moro  ."]},{"name":"Moresco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Primo, Gino, Luciano, Riccardo.","Italian:","(<b>Morésco</b>): from a medieval personal name or a nickname for someone from North Africa or a swarthy or dark-haired man, from medieval Latin <i>Mauriscus</i> ‘Moor’ (see   Moore   2)."]},{"name":"Morey","meanings":["Irish (Limerick and Cork): variant of   Moore   4.","English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Mory</i>, a pet form of <i>Amauri</i> (see   Amery  ).","English: perhaps also a variant of   Moore   1–3."]},{"name":"Morrell","meanings":["English (northern): from the medieval personal name <i>Morel</i>, a diminutive of Middle English or Old French <i>More</i>. Compare   Moore  .","Americanized form of French   Morel  . Compare   Morell   3."]},{"name":"Moores","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cheshire): variant of   Moore  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"McMoore","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Moore   4, in which <i>Mac-</i> ‘son of’ has been prefixed in modern times to give the name (<b>Ó Mórdha</b> ‘descendant of Mórdha’) an unmistakably Gaelic identity."]},{"name":"Moro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Mario, Alberto, Jorge, Lino, Luis, Luiz, Manuel, Ramiro, Adolfo, Aida.  Italian Angelo, Pino, Pio, Remo, Antonio, Ciro, Cosmo, Elio, Enrico, Geno, Giancarlo, Gino.","Spanish: nickname or ethnic name from <i>moro</i> ‘Moor’, from Latin <i>Maurus</i> ‘Moor, North African’.","Italian: nickname from <i>moro</i> ‘Moor’ (see   Moore   2, compare 1 above), also ‘black-haired man’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":17,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas William Moore was born in 1438, in Benenden, Kent, England, his father, John More, was 19 and his mother, Rose Brace, was 14. He married Margaret Catherine Benchley Benenden about 1471, in England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1520, in London, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 82."},"et":{"1438–1520":"1438–1520","1448–Male":"1448–Surnud","1450–1518":"1450–1518","1472–Male":"1472–Surnud","1474–1504":"1474–1504","1500–1591":"1500–1591","1420–Male":"1420–Surnud","1425–Female":"1425–Surnud","1472":"1472","1450":"1450","       1472":"1472","1591":"1591","1448":"1448","1425":"1425","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","about 1449":"umbes 1449","1420":"1420","1474":"1474","about 1500":"umbes 1500","1518":"1518","about 1471":"umbes 1471","1438":"1438","1504":"1504","Of Benenden,Kent,Eng":"Benenden, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Louth, County Louth, Ireland":"Louth, County Louth, Iirimaa","England":"England","Benenden, Kent, England":"Benenden, Kent, England","London, London, England, United Kingdom":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Benenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Benenden, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1438–1520":"1438–1520","1448–Male":"1448–Kuollut","1450–1518":"1450–1518","1472–Male":"1472–Kuollut","1474–1504":"1474–1504","1500–1591":"1500–1591","1420–Male":"1420–Kuollut","1425–Female":"1425–Kuollut","1472":"1472","1450":"1450","       1472":"1472","1591":"1591","1448":"1448","1425":"1425","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","about 1449":"noin 1449","1420":"1420","1474":"1474","ab